# Introduction # {#introduction}

<em>This section is non-normative.</em>

## Product Vision ## {#vision}

CubeMaster is an intelligent, role-play companion device shaped as a
cube. Each of its four lateral faces contains a 16×16 RGB LED grid,
and a speaker provides directional audio output. The cube listens to
the environment via an I2S microphone, detects programmed keywords
using on-device keyword spotting, and plays associated sounds with
synchronized LED animations. The cube's behavior — keyword-to-sound
mappings and LED patterns — is configured via a companion application
over BLE and Wi-Fi.

The companion app is a Dioxus-based cross-platform application
(desktop + mobile) that serves as the control surface for the cube
and as a hub for sharing sound packs between CubeMaster users.

## Architecture Decisions ## {#decisions}

The following high-level decisions were made per the product
requirements:

<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Decision</th><th>Rationale</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>ESP32-S3 microcontroller</td><td>Dual-core RISC-V, 512KB SRAM, 8MB PSRAM, native BLE 5.0 + Wi-Fi, RMT + I2S DMA</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Embassy RTOS (Rust)</td><td>Async executor for ergonomic concurrent tasks</td></tr>
    <tr><td>BLE for control, Wi-Fi for bulk</td><td>BLE is low-latency for commands; Wi-Fi enables fast sound file uploads</td></tr>
    <tr><td>SD card + app streaming</td><td>Dual-mode: onboard SD for standalone playback, Wi-Fi streaming for larger sets</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Dioxus (Rust) companion app</td><td>Single Rust codebase for desktop and mobile</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Cargo workspace monorepo</td><td>Shared protocol crate between firmware and companion app</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

## MVP Scope ## {#mvp-scope}

The MVP targets breadboard development with an ESP32-S3 development
kit powered via USB (no battery management). It includes the full
feature set minus power management:

- 4× 16×16 WS2812B LED panels (one per lateral face)
- 1× MAX98357A I2S amplifier + 1× 3W speaker
- 1× PDM microphone (MP34DT06)
- 1× microSD card slot for sound and pattern storage
- 1× power button, 1× volume button, 1× battery indicator LED
- BLE GATT server for control and configuration
- Wi-Fi server for bulk uploads and streaming
- On-device keyword spotting (VAD + Goertzel KWS)
- Dioxus companion app (desktop first, mobile follow-up)

Inclusions explicitly out of scope for MVP: battery charging circuit,
power path management, multi-cube synchronization, TTS engine, mood
engine, sound pack marketplace, 3D-printed enclosure, custom PCB.

# System Architecture # {#system-architecture}

<em>This section is normative.</em>

## Overview ## {#system-overview}

The CubeMaster system consists of two primary components: the Cube
hardware (ESP32-S3 firmware) and the Companion App (Dioxus). They
communicate over two wireless channels: BLE for low-latency control
and Wi-Fi for bulk data transfer.

<figure>
  <img src="diagrams/img/system-architecture.svg" alt="System architecture overview diagram">
  <figcaption>CubeMaster system architecture — high-level component diagram</figcaption>
</figure>

### Communication Channels ### {#communication-channels}

Two wireless interfaces are used:

1. <strong>BLE (Bluetooth Low Energy)</strong>: Used for all command/control and
    small data transfers. The ESP32-S3 acts as a GATT peripheral with
    three services. BLE is always available regardless of Wi-Fi state.

2. <strong>Wi-Fi (802.11 b/g/n)</strong>: Used for bulk sound file uploads (&gt;10KB)
    and optional audio streaming. The ESP32-S3 runs a lightweight HTTP
    server and WebSocket endpoint when Wi-Fi is configured. Wi-Fi is
    disabled by default to save power; the companion app instructs
    connection when needed.

### Dual Storage Mode ### {#dual-storage}

The cube operates in two storage modes:

<strong>Standalone Mode (SD Card)</strong>: Sounds are pre-loaded onto the
microSD card via BLE upload or direct file copy. The cube plays
sounds directly from SD without requiring the companion app.

<strong>Streaming Mode (Wi-Fi)</strong>: The companion app streams sound data
over Wi-Fi WebSocket or HTTP in real-time. This enables access to
larger sound libraries that don't fit on the SD card.

<div class=issue>
Finalize whether streaming uses WebSocket push from the app or HTTP
pull from a server on the cube. The initial implementation should
support HTTP Chunked Transfer from the cube's HTTP server.
</div>

## Rust Workspace Structure ## {#workspace-structure}

The repository is organized as a Cargo workspace monorepo:

<figure>
  <img src="diagrams/img/repo-architecture.svg" alt="Repository architecture">
  <figcaption>Cargo workspace structure</figcaption>
</figure>

### Crate Descriptions ### {#crate-descriptions}

<dl>
  <dt><code>firmware/</code></dt>
  <dd>
    <code>#![no_std]</code> crate targeting <code>xtensa-esp32s3-none-elf</code>. Contains
    all on-device logic: LED driver, audio playback, voice pipeline,
    BLE GATT server, Wi-Fi server, SD card filesystem, button handler,
    and the main supervisor task loop. Uses Embassy as the async
    executor. Dependencies: <code>esp-hal</code>, <code>esp-radio</code>,
    <code>embassy-executor</code>, <code>embassy-net</code>,
    <code>trouble-host</code>, <code>embedded-sdmmc</code>.
  </dd>

  <dt><code>companion/</code></dt>
  <dd>
    Standard Rust crate built as a Dioxus desktop and mobile
    application. Provides the UI for managing sound banks, configuring
    keyword-to-sound mappings, triggering sounds manually, uploading
    to the cube, and browsing/modifying the cube state. Dependencies:
    <code>dioxus</code>, <code>btleplug</code> (BLE), <code>reqwest</code>
    (Wi-Fi HTTP), <code>cpal</code> (audio preview).
  </dd>

  <dt><code>shared/</code></dt>
  <dd>
    <code>no_std</code>-compatible crate with no target-specific dependencies.
    Contains:
    - Protocol message types (serde-serializable)
    - BLE GATT UUID definitions
    - Sound format constants (sample rate, bit depth, frame size)
    - Keyword configuration data structures
    - LED pattern format definitions
    - Used by both <code>firmware</code> and <code>companion</code>.
  </dd>

  <dt><code>x-tools/</code></dt>
  <dd>
    Developer CLI tool for flashing firmware, formatting SD cards for
    the cube, running integration tests, and generating test sound
    packs. Dependencies: <code>espflash</code>, <code>clap</code>,
    <code>shared</code>.
  </dd>
</dl>

