# Firmware Specification # {#firmware}

<em>This section is normative.</em>

## Execution Model ## {#execution-model}

The firmware uses Embassy as the async executor on the ESP32-S3.
Embassy tasks are spawned at initialization and communicate via
<code>embassy::sync::Channel</code> message passing. The dual-core S3 is fully
utilized: Core 0 handles real-time peripherals (LED RMT DMA, I2S
DMA), while Core 1 handles BLE, Wi-Fi, and voice processing.

## Module Architecture ## {#module-architecture}

<figure>
  <img src="diagrams/img/firmware-architecture.svg" alt="Firmware module architecture">
  <figcaption>Internal firmware module architecture and data flow</figcaption>
</figure>

### Main Supervisor ### {#main-supervisor}

The supervisor is the central orchestrator. It receives events from
peripheral modules, makes decisions based on the current sound/keyword
configuration, and dispatches playback commands.

```rust
// Simplified supervisor event loop
#[embassy_executor::task]
async fn supervisor(
    mut led_cmd: Sender<'static, LedCommand>,
    mut audio_cmd: Sender<'static, AudioCommand>,
    mut ble_rx: Receiver<'static, BleEvent>,
    mut voice_rx: Receiver<'static, VoiceEvent>,
) {
    loop {
        select! {
            BleEvent::Play { sound_id, face, volume } => {
                audio_cmd.send(AudioCommand::Play { id: sound_id, volume, pan: face_to_pan(face) }).await;
                led_cmd.send(LedCommand::PlayPattern { id: sound_id, face }).await;
            }
            BleEvent::UploadStart { .. } => { /* handle chunked upload to SD */ }
            VoiceEvent::Keyword { keyword_id, confidence } => {
                if confidence >= threshold() {
                    let config = get_keyword_config(keyword_id).await;
                    audio_cmd.send(AudioCommand::Play { id: config.sound_id, volume, pan }).await;
                    led_cmd.send(LedCommand::PlayPattern { id: config.pattern_id, face }).await;
                }
            }
        }
    }
}
```

### LED Driver (<code>led_rmt.rs</code>) ### {#led-driver}

Manages four RMT DMA channels, one per LED panel. Each channel drives
256 WS2812B LEDs at 800kHz. Frames are generated by the pattern engine
(procedural noise, keyframe interpolation, or bitmap playback).

<figure>
  <img src="diagrams/img/led-subsystem.svg" alt="LED subsystem detail">
  <figcaption>LED subsystem: pattern engine, frame buffer, and RMT DMA</figcaption>
</figure>

<strong>Performance Budget:</strong>
- Per-LED transmission time: 30µs (24 bits @ 1.25µs/bit)
- Per-chain (256 LEDs): 7.68ms
- 4-ch parallel (DMA concurrent): ~7.68ms/frame
- Target refresh: 30 FPS (33ms period — ample headroom)

<strong>Pattern Types:</strong>
1. Static fill: solid color, brightness 0–255
2. Procedural noise: fire, plasma, rain effects (inline PRNG)
3. Keyframe animation: 8 frames @ 100ms each
4. Bitmap playback: raw RGB frame data from SD (12 frames/second)

### Audio Player (<code>audio_i2s.rs</code>) ### {#audio-player}

Manages I2S DMA output to the MAX98357A amplifier. Audio data is read
from the SD card in chunks and fed into a double-buffered DMA ring.
The mixer supports per-face panning for spatial audio effects (future
multi-speaker expansion).

<figure>
  <img src="diagrams/img/audio-pipeline.svg" alt="Audio playback pipeline">
  <figcaption>Audio pipeline from request to speaker output</figcaption>
</figure>

<strong>Audio Format:</strong>
- Sample rate: 16kHz
- Bit depth: 16-bit signed integer (i16)
- Channels: 1 (mono, panned in software)
- Storage: raw PCM (no header) for minimal decode overhead

<strong>DMA Configuration:</strong>
- Buffer size: 16KB total, split into two 8KB half-buffers
- Half-buffer duration: 256ms (@ 16kHz mono 16-bit)
- IRQ on half-transfer and full-transfer for refill
- Target underrun rate: &lt;1%

### Voice Pipeline (<code>voice_pdm.rs</code>) ### {#voice-pipeline}

Implements on-device keyword spotting with two stages: Voice Activity
Detection (VAD) to gate processing, and Goertzel algorithm for keyword
frequency detection.

<figure>
  <img src="diagrams/img/voice-pipeline.svg" alt="Voice pipeline">
  <figcaption>Voice pipeline: PDM capture → VAD gate → Goertzel KWS</figcaption>
</figure>

<strong>PDM Capture:</strong>
- I2S peripheral in PDM RX mode
- 64× decimation: 1.024MHz PDM → 16kHz PCM
- Frame size: 20ms (320 samples)

<strong>VAD (WebRTC VAD-RS):</strong>
- Algorithm: Gaussian Mixture Model (fixed-point)
- Aggressiveness: mode 2 (balanced)
- Flash cost: ~5KB code + 1KB data
- CPU: ~1% when active

<strong>Goertzel Keyword Spotting:</strong>
- Fixed-point Q15 arithmetic (no float/alloc)
- Per keyword: 2–4 frequency bins with per-bin thresholds
- Keyword configuration stored on SD, updatable via BLE
- Flash cost: ~7KB code + 0.5KB state
- CPU: ~0.5% average (VAD-gated, runs only during speech)
- Latency: &lt;100ms from end of keyword to event dispatch

Example keyword configuration (JSON on SD):

```json
{
  "keywords": [
    {"id": 0, "label": "fire", "bins": [350, 700, 1400], "threshold": 4096},
    {"id": 1, "label": "thunder", "bins": [80, 160, 320], "threshold": 5000},
    {"id": 2, "label": "dragon", "bins": [400, 900, 1500, 2000], "threshold": 3500}
  ]
}
```

### BLE GATT Server (<code>ble_gatt.rs</code>) ### {#ble-gatt}

Implements a BLE peripheral with three GATT services. The stack uses
<code>trouble-host</code> (formerly <code>bt-hci</code>) for BLE.

<figure>
  <img src="diagrams/img/ble-protocol.svg" alt="BLE protocol sequence">
  <figcaption>BLE GATT protocol: advertisement, services, and upload flow</figcaption>
</figure>

#### Service 1: Control Service (UUID: 0000FFE0-…) #### {#ble-control}

<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Characteristic</th><th>UUID</th><th>Properties</th><th>Description</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>CMD</td><td>FFE1</td><td>Write</td><td>Trigger playback, set volume, etc.</td></tr>
    <tr><td>STATUS</td><td>FFE2</td><td>Notify</td><td>Playing state, battery, errors</td></tr>
    <tr><td>CONFIG</td><td>FFE3</td><td>Write, Read</td><td>Keyword map, settings</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

CMD payload (JSON-like, max 64B):

```json
{"cmd":"play","id":0,"face":1,"volume":80}
```

STATUS notification:

```json
{"state":"playing","id":0,"progress":75,"battery":0,"rssi":-50}
```

#### Service 2: Upload Service (UUID: 0000FFE1-…) #### {#ble-upload}

<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Characteristic</th><th>UUID</th><th>Properties</th><th>Description</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>START</td><td>FFE4</td><td>Write</td><td>File metadata (id, name, length)</td></tr>
    <tr><td>CHUNK</td><td>FFE5</td><td>Write</td><td>512B raw data chunk</td></tr>
    <tr><td>DONE</td><td>FFE6</td><td>Write</td><td>Finalize upload + keyword mapping</td></tr>
    <tr><td>LIST</td><td>FFE7</td><td>Read, Notify</td><td>List of sounds on SD with free space</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

#### Service 3: LED Patterns (UUID: 0000FFE2-…) #### {#ble-patterns}

<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Characteristic</th><th>UUID</th><th>Properties</th><th>Description</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>PATTERN</td><td>FFE8</td><td>Write</td><td>Compressed LED frame data</td></tr>
    <tr><td>PATTERN_LIST</td><td>FFE9</td><td>Read, Notify</td><td>List of stored patterns</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

### Wi-Fi Server (<code>wifi_server.rs</code>) ### {#wifi-server}

The Wi-Fi server is conditionally started by the companion app via a
BLE command. It provides:

1. <strong>HTTP GET <code>/sounds/{id}</code></strong>: Stream a sound file from SD
2. <strong>HTTP POST <code>/upload</code></strong>: Receive a sound file bulk upload
3. <strong>WebSocket <code>/ws</code></strong>: Bidirectional streaming for control + audio

Wi-Fi is disabled by default to save power. Enable sequence:

1. App sends BLE <code>CMD</code> with Wi-Fi credentials
2. Cube connects, starts HTTP server on port 8080
3. Cube notifies its IP address via BLE <code>STATUS</code>
4. App connects via Wi-Fi for bulk operations

### SD Card FS (<code>sd_fs.rs</code>) ### {#sd-fs}

Manages the FAT32 filesystem on the microSD card via SPI. Directory
structure:

```
/sounds/
  0.pcm         # Sound ID 0 (raw PCM 16-bit mono 16kHz)
  1.pcm         # Sound ID 1
  ...
  config.json   # Sound metadata (name, keyword mapping)
/patterns/
  0.bin         # LED pattern ID 0 (raw RGB frames)
  1.bin
  ...
/kw_config.json # Keyword spotter configuration
```

Operations: <code>read(id)</code>, <code>write(id, data)</code>, <code>list()</code>, <code>delete(id)</code>,
<code>free_space()</code>.

### Button Handler (<code>btn_mon.rs</code>) ### {#button-handler}

Two buttons via GPIO interrupts with software debounce:

<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Button</th><th>Press (&lt;1s)</th><th>Hold (1–3s)</th><th>Hold (&gt;3s)</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>Power (GPIO0)</td><td>Toggle LED on/off</td><td>Volume mute</td><td>Deep sleep</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Volume (GPIO1)</td><td>Cycle volume (0% → 25% → 50% → 75% → 100%)</td><td>—</td><td>Factory reset</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

### Battery Monitor (<code>batt_mon.rs</code>) ### {#battery-monitor}

Reads battery voltage via ADC (voltage divider). For MVP
(breadboard/USB-powered), this monitors the USB 5V rail presence as
a proxy. The battery LED blinks patterns:

- Solid green: powered, idle
- Pulsing blue: BLE connected
- Fast blink orange: uploading
- Slow blink red: error/overheat

# Companion App Specification # {#companion-app}

<em>This section is normative.</em>

## Technology Stack ## {#app-stack}

The companion app is built with <strong>Dioxus</strong>, a Rust reactive UI
framework, compiled to native desktop (via WGPU) and mobile (via
platform WebView). Platform targets:

<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Platform</th><th>Renderer</th><th>Phase</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>Linux</td><td>Dioxus Desktop</td><td>MVP</td></tr>
    <tr><td>macOS</td><td>Dioxus Desktop</td><td>MVP</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Windows</td><td>Dioxus Desktop</td><td>MVP</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Android</td><td>Dioxus Mobile</td><td>Post-MVP</td></tr>
    <tr><td>iOS</td><td>Dioxus Mobile</td><td>Post-MVP</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

Dependencies: <code>dioxus</code>, <code>btleplug</code> (cross-platform BLE), <code>reqwest</code>
(HTTP/WebSocket), <code>cpal</code> (local audio preview), <code>serde</code>/<code>serde_json</code>.

## Features ## {#app-features}

### Sound Bank Management ### {#app-soundbank}

The app manages collections of sounds called "Sound Banks". A sound
bank is a JSON manifest referencing local audio files:

```json
{
  "name": "D&D Fire Module",
  "author": "gm_alice",
  "version": 1,
  "sounds": [
    {"id": 0, "path": "fire_ignite.pcm", "keyword": "fire", "led_pattern": "fire"},
    {"id": 1, "path": "explosion.pcm", "keyword": "thunder", "led_pattern": "explosion"}
  ]
}
```

Sound banks can be exported to files, imported from others, and
shared via the companion app hub (post-MVP marketplace).

### Cube Management ### {#app-cube}

- <strong>BLE Scanning</strong>: Discover nearby CubeMaster devices
- <strong>Connection Management</strong>: Pair, connect, disconnect
- <strong>Sound Upload</strong>: Select a sound bank → upload all files via BLE or
    Wi-Fi bulk
- <strong>Keyword Configuration</strong>: Assign keywords to sounds, adjust
    detection thresholds
- <strong>LED Preview</strong>: Preview LED patterns on a simulated cube face
- <strong>Live Control</strong>: Trigger sounds manually, adjust volume, play
    sequences
- <strong>Cube Status</strong>: Battery level, SD free space, firmware version,
    Wi-Fi status

### Sound Pack Hub (Post-MVP) ### {#app-hub}

A community hub for sharing and discovering sound packs. Sound packs
include audio files, LED patterns, and keyword configurations. The hub
supports browsing, downloading, rating, and remixing packs.

## App-Firmware Communication Flow ## {#app-comm-flow}

<strong>Connection sequence:</strong>

1. App scans for BLE devices advertising "CubeMaster-XXXX"
2. App connects, negotiates MTU 512
3. App reads STATUS characteristic for cube state
4. If Wi-Fi desired, app sends Wi-Fi credentials via BLE CMD
5. Cube connects to Wi-Fi and notifies its IP via BLE STATUS

<strong>Upload sequence (BLE, small files):</strong>

1. App writes START characteristic with file metadata
2. App iterates CHUNK writes (512B each)
3. App writes DONE with keyword mapping
4. Cube acknowledges via STATUS notification

<strong>Upload sequence (Wi-Fi, large files):</strong>

1. App sends HTTP POST to <code>/upload</code> on cube's Wi-Fi IP
2. Cube streams file to SD, returns 200 OK
3. App sends keyword mapping via BLE CONFIG write

## UI Components ## {#app-ui}

### Main Views ### {#app-views}

<dl>
  <dt>Sound Bank View</dt>
  <dd>
    Browse local sound banks, create new banks, import/export. Shows
    a grid of sound banks with metadata (name, sound count, size).
  </dd>

  <dt>Cube View</dt>
  <dd>
    Connected cube status dashboard. Shows BLE signal strength, SD
    free space, current configuration, and playback state.
  </dd>

  <dt>Editor View</dt>
  <dd>
    Assign keywords to sounds, fine-tune VAD thresholds, map LED
    patterns to sounds, configure sequences.
  </dd>

  <dt>Live Control View</dt>
  <dd>
    Big trigger buttons for each sound, volume slider, panic button
    (stop all), ambiance mode toggle.
  </dd>

  <dt>Hub View (Post-MVP)</dt>
  <dd>
    Browse community sound packs, download, rate, and share.
  </dd>
</dl>

# Protocol Specification # {#protocol}

<em>This section is normative.</em>

## BLE Message Format ## {#ble-protocol}

All BLE messages use a compact binary-wrapped JSON format. The first
byte identifies the message type, followed by a JSON payload:

```
[type: u8][json_payload: N bytes]
```

Message types:

<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Type</th><th>Name</th><th>Direction</th><th>Description</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>0x01</td><td>CMD_PLAY</td><td>App → Cube</td><td>Trigger sound playback</td></tr>
    <tr><td>0x02</td><td>CMD_STOP</td><td>App → Cube</td><td>Stop current playback</td></tr>
    <tr><td>0x03</td><td>CMD_VOLUME</td><td>App → Cube</td><td>Set volume 0–100</td></tr>
    <tr><td>0x04</td><td>CMD_WIFI_CONFIG</td><td>App → Cube</td><td>SSID + password</td></tr>
    <tr><td>0x05</td><td>STATUS_UPDATE</td><td>Cube → App</td><td>Periodic status</td></tr>
    <tr><td>0x06</td><td>UPLOAD_START</td><td>App → Cube</td><td>Begin file upload</td></tr>
    <tr><td>0x07</td><td>UPLOAD_CHUNK</td><td>App → Cube</td><td>Data chunk</td></tr>
    <tr><td>0x08</td><td>UPLOAD_DONE</td><td>App → Cube</td><td>Finalize upload</td></tr>
    <tr><td>0x09</td><td>CONFIG_KW</td><td>App → Cube</td><td>Update keyword settings</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

## Wi-Fi HTTP API ## {#wifi-api}

The cube's HTTP server listens on port 8080.

<dl>
  <dt><code>GET /status</code></dt>
  <dd>
    Returns JSON cube status:
    <code>{"firmware":"0.1.0","uptime":12345,"sd_free":524288000,"ble_clients":1,"playing":null}</code>
  </dd>

  <dt><code>GET /sounds</code></dt>
  <dd>
    Returns JSON array of sound metadata:
    <code>[{"id":0,"name":"fire","size":40000,"keyword":"fire"}, ...]</code>
  </dd>

  <dt><code>GET /sounds/{id}</code></dt>
  <dd>
    Streams raw PCM data with <code>Content-Type: audio/pcm16</code>.
    Supports <code>Range</code> header for seeking.
  </dd>

  <dt><code>POST /upload</code></dt>
  <dd>
    Accepts multipart form data with fields: <code>file</code> (raw PCM),
    <code>name</code>, <code>keyword</code>, <code>pattern_id</code>.
    Returns <code>{"id": 3, "size": 40000}</code>.
  </dd>

  <dt><code>DELETE /sounds/{id}</code></dt>
  <dd>
    Deletes a sound from SD. Returns 204.
  </dd>

  <dt>WebSocket /ws</dt>
  <dd>
    Bidirectional control channel. Messages are JSON frames with type
    and payload. Supports real-time playback commands and status streaming.
  </dd>
</dl>

# Performance Budget # {#performance}

## Resource Limits ## {#resource-limits}

<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Resource</th><th>Budget</th><th>Measured/Target</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>Flash</td><td>&lt;1MB</td><td>Firmware target ~500KB</td></tr>
    <tr><td>RAM (static)</td><td>&lt;50KB</td><td>Buffers + stacks ~32KB</td></tr>
    <tr><td>CPU (Core 0)</td><td>&lt;60%</td><td>LED DMA + I2S DMA &lt;30%</td></tr>
    <tr><td>CPU (Core 1)</td><td>&lt;60%</td><td>BLE poll + Voice &lt;20%</td></tr>
    <tr><td>BLE throughput</td><td>~20KB/s</td><td>Upload 40KB = 2s</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Wi-Fi throughput</td><td>~1MB/s</td><td>Upload 1MB = 1s</td></tr>
    <tr><td>LED refresh</td><td>30 FPS target</td><td>Parallel DMA ~100 FPS max</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Audio latency</td><td>&lt;100ms</td><td>DMA buffer = 256ms half</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Voice latency</td><td>&lt;100ms</td><td>VAD 5ms + Goertzel 2ms</td></tr>
    <tr><td>BLE range</td><td>&gt;10m indoor</td><td>BLE 5.0 coded PHY</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Power (USB)</td><td>&lt;2.5A @5V</td><td>Peak 5.5A limited to 2.5A</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

## Firmware Size Budget ## {#size-budget}

<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Component</th><th>Flash</th><th>RAM</th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>esp-hal + RTOS</td><td>120KB</td><td>8KB</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Embassy executor</td><td>30KB</td><td>4KB</td></tr>
    <tr><td>BLE stack (trouble-host)</td><td>150KB</td><td>8KB</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Wi-Fi stack</td><td>80KB</td><td>6KB</td></tr>
    <tr><td>LED driver</td><td>8KB</td><td>4KB</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Audio driver</td><td>12KB</td><td>18KB</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Voice (VAD+KWS)</td><td>12KB</td><td>2KB</td></tr>
    <tr><td>SD FS</td><td>20KB</td><td>4KB</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Supervisor + Utils</td><td>20KB</td><td>4KB</td></tr>
    <tr><td><b>Total</b></td><td><b>~452KB</b></td><td><b>~58KB</b></td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

# Security Considerations # {#security}

<em>This section is non-normative.</em>

- BLE pairing: Just Works for MVP. Future versions should implement
    numeric comparison pairing for production.
- Wi-Fi credentials: Stored in plaintext on the cube's NVS partition.
    Consider encrypting with a device-specific key in production.
- HTTP server: No authentication. Only accessible on the local network
    segment. Consider adding a simple pre-shared key for production.
- SD card: No encryption. Sound files are user-generated content with
    no sensitive data.

# Post-MVP Features # {#post-mvp}

The following features are deferred to post-MVP development cycles:

1. <strong>Mood Engine</strong>: Ambient-reactive mode that autonomously plays
    background ambiance based on time, detected activity level, or
    a game master's scenario cues.
2. <strong>Sound Pack Marketplace</strong>: In-app hub for discovering, rating,
    and sharing community-created sound packs.
3. <strong>Multi-Cube Sync</strong>: Multiple CubeMaster devices synchronized for
    immersive multi-directional audio and lighting (e.g., D&amp;D table).
4. <strong>Ambient Reactive Mode</strong>: Continuous environmental monitoring
    (light level, sound level) to auto-adjust cube ambiance.
5. <strong>TTS Engine</strong>: Text-to-speech synthesis for dynamic narration,
    eliminating the need for pre-recorded dialogue.
6. <strong>Battery Management</strong>: Full USB-C PD charging, 3S LiPo BMS, power
    path management, deep sleep optimization.
7. <strong>Custom PCB</strong>: JLCPCB-fabricated custom mainboard replacing the
    breadboard + dev kit prototype.
8. <strong>3D-Printed Enclosure</strong>: 200mm cube frame with frosted acrylic
    diffusers and speaker grilles.
9. <strong>Mobile Companion App</strong>: Dioxus Mobile builds for Android and iOS.

# Conformance # {#conformance}

There is only one class of product: the CubeMaster.

## Conformance Classes ## {#conformance-classes}

A product implementing the CubeMaster firmware MUST:

- Advertise as a BLE peripheral with the device name prefix
    "CubeMaster-"
- Implement the three GATT services defined in [[#ble-gatt]]
- Accept PCM 16-bit mono 16kHz audio data via both BLE upload and
    Wi-Fi HTTP POST
- Detect keywords per the Goertzel configuration stored on SD
- Drive WS2812B LEDs via RMT DMA at the configured pinout
- Output audio via I2S DMA to a MAX98357A or equivalent amplifier

A product implementing the CubeMaster companion app MUST:

- Discover and connect to CubeMaster BLE peripherals
- Upload sound files via the defined BLE upload protocol
- Configure keyword-to-sound mappings on the cube
- Support manual sound triggering from the UI
- Operate on at least one desktop platform (Linux, macOS, or Windows)
